  doi = {10.1002/jmv.28099},
  abstract = {AbstractBackgroundWhile the number of detected Monkeypox infections are widely available, an understanding of the extent of undetected cases is urgently needed for an effective tackling of its spread. The aim of this work is to estimate the true number of Monkeypox (detected and undetected) infections in most affected countries. The question being asked is: How many cases have actually occurred?MethodsWe propose a lower bound estimator for the true number of Monkeypox cases. The estimator is data-driven and can be easily computed from the cumulative distributions of weekly cases.ResultsWe focused on the ratio of the total estimated cases to the observed cases at July 31st 2022: the proportion of undetected cases was relevant in all countries, with countries whose estimated true number of infections could be more than three times the observed one.ConclusionsWe provided a practical contribution to the understanding of the current Monkeypox wave and reliable estimates on how many undetected cases are going around for several countries, where the epidemic spreads differently.This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.},
